│ stop({"edit_points": [[2648, 2668,                                                     │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the │
│ Issue:\nThe crash manifests as an assertion failure in                                 │
│ BoUpSLP::removeInstructionsAndOperands, specifically:\n  (I->use_empty() ||            │
│ all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) { return isDeleted(cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()));      │
│ }))\nThis function drops references of instructions we intend to delete, and then      │
│ asserts that either the instruction has no users or all users are themselves marked    │
│ for deletion. In this reproducer, that invariant is violated: some users of an         │
│ instruction being erased are not marked in DeletedInstructions at the time of the      │
│ check, causing the abort.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe SLP logs show a sequence of  │
│ horizontal reduction vectorizations, erasing various scalar ops (adds, phis, extracts) │
│ in two waves. During the first reduction, many scalars are \"Erasing scalar:\" and     │
│ some users are noted as \"Internal user will be removed\" but not immediately marked   │
│ deleted. The second reduction continues and then attempts to erase PHIs and            │
│ extractelements, ultimately hitting the assert in removeInstructionsAndOperands after  │
│ dropAllReferences.\nThe core pattern is:\n- We add initial DeadVals to                 │
│ DeletedInstructions.\n- We drop all references of I.\n- Then we assert all users of I  │
│ are marked deleted.\nHowever, the pass updates/erases a web of dependent instructions  │
│ incrementally. Some users of I are still live (not yet in DeletedInstructions) when    │
│ this function reaches the assert, even though they will be removed later in the same   │
│ overall transformation sequence.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe function assumes a    │
│ strong invariant: before physical removal of an instruction, either all its uses have  │
│ been rewritten away, or all users are marked for deletion. In horizontal reduction     │
│ vectorization in this reproducer, we are erasing a set of instructions where the users │
│ are part of the same transformation but not yet marked DeletedInstructions.            │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands only pre-marks the DeadVals themselves into              │
│ DeletedInstructions (at the start), but it does not pre-mark their users. As a result, │
│ when we check the invariant, some users of I are not yet in DeletedInstructions,       │
│ violating the assert, even though they are about to be removed in subsequent           │
│ steps.\nThus, the problem is a missed pre-marking of users that are being implicitly   │
│ deleted as part of the current removal operation. Since dropAllReferences does not     │
│ clear the use list, the assert must rely on DeletedInstructions containing those       │
│ users. We need to ensure that all users of the instructions we are erasing are marked  │
│ as deleted before the assert runs, to maintain the invariant.\n\n4. Proposed Edit      │
│ Point(s):\nWe should update removeInstructionsAndOperands to proactively mark all      │
│ instruction users of the DeadVals as deleted before the assert block. This matches the │
│ intended contract: any instruction slated for deletion should have its users either    │
│ rewritten or themselves marked for deletion. The change is localized and preserves the │
│ existing logic.\n\nEdit at llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp lines       │
│ 2648-2668:\n- After salvaging debug info and before I->dropAllReferences(), iterate    │
│ over I->uses() and, for each user that is an Instruction, insert it into               │
│ DeletedInstructions. This ensures the subsequent assert sees all remaining users as    │
│ \"deleted\" as per the set, aligning with the invariant.\n\nConcretely, add:\n  for    │
│ (Use &UseRef : I->uses()) {\n    if (auto *UserI =                                     │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(UseRef.getUser()))\n      DeletedInstructions.insert(UserI);\n   │
│ }\njust before I->dropAllReferences().\n\nThis change does not erase the users         │
│ immediately; it only marks them, which is consistent with the delayed deletion model   │
│ of BoUpSLP and the assert expectations. Users that should remain live must have had    │
│ their operands replaced before this point, in which case they would not be in the      │
│ use-list of I and this marking does nothing. Users that are part of the same removal   │
│ wave are now properly marked deleted.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is due to           │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands asserting that all users of an instruction being removed │
│ are marked as deleted, but the code did not pre-mark those users. By marking all       │
│ instruction users of DeadVals into DeletedInstructions before dropping references and  │
│ removal, we satisfy the invariant and prevent the assertion failure. This aligns with  │
│ the delayed deletion design and with the pass semantics in the face of complex         │
│ reduction vectorization transformations."})                                            │
