│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                            │
│                                                                                        │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                        │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                            │
│ The crash manifests as an assertion failure in BoUpSLP::removeInstructionsAndOperands, │
│ specifically:                                                                          │
│   (I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) { return                            │
│ isDeleted(cast<Instruction>(U.getUser())); }))                                         │
│ This function drops references of instructions we intend to delete, and then asserts   │
│ that either the instruction has no users or all users are themselves marked for        │
│ deletion. In this reproducer, that invariant is violated: some users of an instruction │
│ being erased are not marked in DeletedInstructions at the time of the check, causing   │
│ the abort.                                                                             │
│                                                                                        │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                                │
│ The SLP logs show a sequence of horizontal reduction vectorizations, erasing various   │
│ scalar ops (adds, phis, extracts) in two waves. During the first reduction, many       │
│ scalars are "Erasing scalar:" and some users are noted as "Internal user will be       │
│ removed" but not immediately marked deleted. The second reduction continues and then   │
│ attempts to erase PHIs and extractelements, ultimately hitting the assert in           │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands after dropAllReferences.                                 │
│ The core pattern is:                                                                   │
│ - We add initial DeadVals to DeletedInstructions.                                      │
│ - We drop all references of I.                                                         │
│ - Then we assert all users of I are marked deleted.                                    │
│ However, the pass updates/erases a web of dependent instructions incrementally. Some   │
│ users of I are still live (not yet in DeletedInstructions) when this function reaches  │
│ the assert, even though they will be removed later in the same overall transformation  │
│ sequence.                                                                              │
│                                                                                        │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                │
│ The function assumes a strong invariant: before physical removal of an instruction,    │
│ either all its uses have been rewritten away, or all users are marked for deletion. In │
│ horizontal reduction vectorization in this reproducer, we are erasing a set of         │
│ instructions where the users are part of the same transformation but not yet marked    │
│ DeletedInstructions. removeInstructionsAndOperands only pre-marks the DeadVals         │
│ themselves into DeletedInstructions (at the start), but it does not pre-mark their     │
│ users. As a result, when we check the invariant, some users of I are not yet in        │
│ DeletedInstructions, violating the assert, even though they are about to be removed in │
│ subsequent steps.                                                                      │
│ Thus, the problem is a missed pre-marking of users that are being implicitly deleted   │
│ as part of the current removal operation. Since dropAllReferences does not clear the   │
│ use list, the assert must rely on DeletedInstructions containing those users. We need  │
│ to ensure that all users of the instructions we are erasing are marked as deleted      │
│ before the assert runs, to maintain the invariant.                                     │
│                                                                                        │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                             │
│ We should update removeInstructionsAndOperands to proactively mark all instruction     │
│ users of the DeadVals as deleted before the assert block. This matches the intended    │
│ contract: any instruction slated for deletion should have its users either rewritten   │
│ or themselves marked for deletion. The change is localized and preserves the existing  │
│ logic.                                                                                 │
│                                                                                        │
│ Edit at llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp lines 2648-2668:               │
│ - After salvaging debug info and before I->dropAllReferences(), iterate over I->uses() │
│ and, for each user that is an Instruction, insert it into DeletedInstructions. This    │
│ ensures the subsequent assert sees all remaining users as "deleted" as per the set,    │
│ aligning with the invariant.                                                           │
│                                                                                        │
│ Concretely, add:                                                                       │
│   for (Use &UseRef : I->uses()) {                                                      │
│     if (auto *UserI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(UseRef.getUser()))                         │
│       DeletedInstructions.insert(UserI);                                               │
│   }                                                                                    │
│ just before I->dropAllReferences().                                                    │
│                                                                                        │
│ This change does not erase the users immediately; it only marks them, which is         │
│ consistent with the delayed deletion model of BoUpSLP and the assert expectations.     │
│ Users that should remain live must have had their operands replaced before this point, │
│ in which case they would not be in the use-list of I and this marking does nothing.    │
│ Users that are part of the same removal wave are now properly marked deleted.          │
│                                                                                        │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                         │
│ The crash is due to removeInstructionsAndOperands asserting that all users of an       │
│ instruction being removed are marked as deleted, but the code did not pre-mark those   │
│ users. By marking all instruction users of DeadVals into DeletedInstructions before    │
│ dropping references and removal, we satisfy the invariant and prevent the assertion    │
│ failure. This aligns with the delayed deletion design and with the pass semantics in   │
│ the face of complex reduction vectorization transformations.                           │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                        │
